>I think free will is the contradiction of the 'di' and the 'aletheia'.

Huge fan of the claim. Given that it may require an unmoved mover theory (perhaps as well as an account of what it means for there to be ends in themselves), that seems to be the case. The conditions for the possibility of free will seem to imply there's more to that contradiction. I suggest you would agree with that.

> I think the purpose of my life overlaps with the principles of "be a good dad" and "be a good husband" that you have on your website.

Those are near and dear to me as well. Perhaps there is more to think about here together. It seems to be that you may need to attempt to give an account of the foundations of those principles, sufficient reasons for why. Here there appears to be more work [[The Dialetheia]] does.

